IMDB Movie Review Prediction Model¶

1 Defining the Problem¶

In this project, we define the problem as creating a high accuracy binary classification model that would predict whether an International Movie Data Base (IMDB) review is positive or negative. The data is obtained from tensorflow keras library's official datasets. The input data is 50,000 movie reviews that were manually labeled as positive or negative. The database is divided in half into 25,000 training data and 25,000 testing data with each dataset having 50% positive and 50% negative reviews. The binary classification model can be predicted using this input dataset. Finally, the dataset is easily accessible and informative to create a proper model.

2 Measure of Success¶

In simple binary classification problems it is usually easiest to use accuracy especially in this dataset that the data is very balanced and predicting the negative reviews correctly is as important as predicting the positive reviews correctly. Hence, the aim is to create a model with high accuray and the fine-tuning of the hyperparameters depends on the accuracy acheived in each training.

3 Evaluation Protocol¶

Using simple hold-out evaluation in this project should work well since we have a large dataset available to evaluate the model. To do this, I will use the following code: model.evaluate(x_val,y_val) to explicity evaluate the model on the held-out validation data set as stated in DLWP.

4.3 Vectorizing the Data¶

We will vectorize the dataset to be able to manipulate the data properly using the simple code below:

In [5]:
#from DLWP/Lectures
import numpy as np

def vectorize_sequences(sequences, dimension = 10000):
    results = np.zeros( (len(sequences), dimension) )
    for i, sequence in enumerate(sequences):
        results[i, sequence] = 1.
    return results

x_train = vectorize_sequences(train_data)
x_test = vectorize_sequences(test_data)

y_train = np.asarray(train_labels).astype('float32') 
y_test =  np.asarray(test_labels).astype('float32')

#defining plot loss and accuracy functions against the training and validation dataset
# Inspired by lectures/lab - I created my own function to stop repeating the plot function
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_loss(loss_values, val_loss_values, epochs):
    plt.plot(epochs, loss_values, 'ro', label='Training loss')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss_values, 'r', label='Validation loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
def plot_acc(acc, val_acc, epochs):
    plt.plot(epochs, acc, 'go', label='Training acc')
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, 'g', label='Validation acc')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

epochs = range(1, len(loss_values) + 1)

plot_loss(loss_values, val_loss_values,epochs)
plot_acc(acc, val_acc,epochs)

8 Conclusions¶

In this project, we successfully created a model to predict the IMDB reviews as positive or negative. We were able to fine tune the model's accuracy and increase from 87.78% to a maximum of 88.80% as shown below in the final model evaluation. We explored different combination of model architectures, epoch values, dropout layers, L1 and L2 values, and layer capacity. Finally, after training the model over different hyperparameters, we fine-tune the model to the model shown below, with drop out value of 0.3, 4 relu-layer, relu-layer capacity of 512, 4 hidden dropout layers, 1 sigmoid layer, and decided not to add any L1/L2 parameters to the final model.

# Final Model
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu', input_shape=(10000,)))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
model.add(layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

model.compile(optimizer='rmsprop', 
              loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
              metrics = ['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(partial_x_train, partial_y_train, epochs = 20, batch_size = 512, validation_data= (x_val, y_val))
results = model.evaluate(x_val, y_val)
